(Intermediate) Quest 9: Capstone Project - Game Frontend with ERC721 Token SC
Introduction
In the previous quest, we learnt how we can deploy an ERC721 token smart contract using the Hardhat framework. For this quest, we will be building a simple memory game using React that requires players to match 4 sets of cards that are arranged randomly. 
Once a match is found, an Non-Fungible Token (NFT) of the matching image will be minted on the Avalanche Fuji Testnet C-Chain using the Ethers.js library to interact with the token smart contract. The images for the NFTs will be stored on IPFS using Pinata. We will also be connecting our own wallets so that the NFTs will be minted directly to our wallets.

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe the Ethers.js library
  • Use Pinata to upload images to IPFS
  • Interact with a deployed smart contract using the Ethers.js library
Deliverable
This quest has two deliverables, refer to Step 9 for more details.
  1. A screenshot of your web page after completing the challenge.
  2. A screenshot of the transaction details of the minting of a token on SnowTrace.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Ethers.js
Ethers.js is a JavaScript library for interacting with the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) compatible blockchains such as Avalanche. Some of its features include importing and exporting wallets, creating JavaScript objects from contract ABIs (Application Binary Interface) which will be covered in a later step, interacting with deployed smart contracts, reading and writing the blockchain, and many others. 
Since learning about all of Ethers.js’ features and functionalities is outside the scope of this campaign, if you’re interested in learning more about Ethers.js, please refer to our Ethers.js for Blockchain Interaction Module. However, we’ll be covering the essentials of what Ethers.js can do in this quest as well as in Quest 11. For this quest, we’ll be using Ethers.js mainly for the creation of the JavaScript objects that will be used to interact with the NFT smart contract we deployed in Quest 8. If you haven’t completed Quest 8 yet, make sure to do so before proceeding with this quest!
Step 2: Setting Up Pinata Account
In the previous quest, we learned what IPFS is and its applications in relation to NFTs, mainly that it is used to store the image of the NFT. For this step, we will be going through what Pinata is, how to set up an account and getting a Pinata API key.  
Pinata is one of the available IPFS platforms that allows storage of image and image metadata. The reason why we are using Pinata is because they have a ready-made API server that we can utilize to easily store and retrieve data from IPFS. Once the image is uploaded, users can access their images using their respective URLs. Pinata provides a free account but has a limit of 100 uploaded files, so do take note of that. 

Let’s sign up for the free account by visiting this site. Once you have signed up for an account and logged in, follow the instructions below. The list item numbers corresponds to the numbers annotated in the image.



  1. Click on API Keys
  2. The page should change. Then, click on + New Key. After doing so, a pop-up should appear
  3. Expand the ‘Pinning’ dropdown menu. Then, toggle on pinFileToIPFS - enabling this will allow us to use the Pinata API endpoint to upload and store our images
  4. Enter Test Key as your key name
  5. Press on Create Key - this will generate the API Key, API Secret and JWT values which it will display in the next pop-up. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference on what to expect

Additional information: JSON Web Token, or JWT, is an open industry standard RCC 7519 method for representing claims securely between two parties. Since JWT is not the focus of this quest, we won’t be covering JWT further but we encourage you to search it up on your own if you’re interested to find out more!

For this quest, we will need the API Key and API Secret values so do copy it down somewhere secure as the information will not be available once the pop-up has been closed. In the event that you lose or forgot your key, you will need to repeat the instructions in this step to generate a new key. 

So now that we have generated our API Key and API Secret for our Pinata API, we will now move on to cloning our project repository and setting up our project!

Step 4: Project Setup
For this step we will be cloning the project into our local directory, doing the necessary configurations and starting the web server.
As we have done in the previous quest, we will need to clone the project from the GitHub repository using git. To clone this project, run the command below in your terminal in your desired file location. 

git clone -b avax-quest-9 https://github.com/stackup-dev/advancing-into-avalanche.git

Once the cloning is done, we will need to change the directory of our terminal to the base of the project file. We can do so using the command below.

cd advancing-into-avalanche
 
Once you have changed the directory, we will need to install the libraries like we did for the other quests and we will do so by using the following command. 

npm install

Troubleshooting: If you face issues while running the command above, it might be because you’re using a version of Node that isn’t supported. Try changing the version of Node you’re using to v16.16.0.

You will also need to have the Core wallet installed and configured. If you have gone through Quest 8 then your Core wallet should have been configured and have some Testnet tokens. As a sanity check, open your Core wallet and check that you are 1) connected to the Avalanche (C-Chain) network, 2) have ‘Developer Mode’ toggled on and 3) ‘Set as Default Extension’ is toggled on.

Since we’re using the deployed ERC721 smart contract that we deployed in the previous quest, we’ll need to get its contract address. This is needed so that the ether.js library knows which contract to call for the minting process.  

You will also need to copy and paste your Pinata API Key and Secret to replace the 2 values in lines 4 and 5 of the src/util/PinataConnection.js file respectively. 

With this, you have the necessary files and configuration needed to run the application. Like the other applications that we have done before, to run it, we will need to run the following command. After doing so, you should have a web page that automatically opens up in your browser which looks like the image in ‘Expected output’.

npm run start

Troubleshooting: If your web page does not open automatically, you might need to manually open the page by visiting http://localhost:3000 in your browser.

Now that we have our application up and running, we will now add in the code necessary for connecting our wallet to the web page and thus, allowing interaction with our deployed ERC721 token smart contract.

Step 5: Connecting Our Wallet
Now let’s see how we can connect our Core wallet to the web page we just deployed. We’ll go through the ether.js functions that we will be using for this application. All the ether.js functions can be found in the src/util/EtherJSFunctions.js file. Let’s open this file to take a closer look.
Let’s first look at the function that enables our wallet connectivity, this is the connectToWallet() function. Inside this function, you will need to copy and paste in the following code. After pasting in the code and saving your script, you should get a pop-up from Core asking for your permission to connect your wallet to the site, click on ‘Approve’. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference. If the pop-up asks you which wallet you would like to use, select Core.

const provider = new ethers.providers.Web3Provider(window.ethereum);  await provider.send("eth_requestAccounts", []);  return provider.getSigner();

Now let’s break down how these three lines of code enable our wallet to connect to the web page.

The first line of code starts the connection to the blockchain network so that we are able to access the Fuji Testnet. The network configurations will be based on the Core configuration which is why in the earlier step we asked to check if your Core wallet has been configured. This is why there is no need to specify which network we want to connect to in the code. 

The second line of code will trigger the Core wallet to confirm if you want to connect to the application. Choosing to connect will allow the application to get data from the Core wallet. 

The last line of code gets the signer object which contains the wallet details such as the private key, address, etc. This object will be used to sign transactions such as the minting of the NFT. This signer object is then returned as an output of the function.

Now let’s take a brief look at where this function is called and how it is used.  

Open up the src/App.js file. If you’re not familiar with React, the contents of this file might seem very foreign to you. Essentially, React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces; App.js contains the majority of the code that is used to build the user interface of our game.

Here, we’ll highlight the useEffect function in line 126. Without going too deep into React’s useEffect function, these functions are basically triggered every time the page is rendered or re-rendered and we have set it up such that only this useEffect function will only be triggered after the first render. Any subsequent renders will not trigger this useEffect making it suitable for our connectToWallet() function as we only want it to trigger once and not every time there is a change.  

Earlier, we have learned that the connectToWallet() would return the signer object so how do we check if the wallet has been successfully connected? Well, how we check that is by getting the wallet address from the signer object and if the wallet address is empty, we can assume that it has not successfully connected and thus indicates that we should stop any subsequent program executions since we’re not ready to proceed.

Note: You will only need to connect once as Core would add this site as a connected site. To view this, open your Core wallet -> menu -> Security & Privacy -> Connected Sites and you’ll see that localhost has been added. So, if you were to refresh the page, it would not prompt you again as it already has your permission to connect to the application and would just pass the information along to the application.  

Now that we’ve enabled wallet connectivity to our game, in the next step we’ll go through how we can create the contract object that will be used to interact with the ERC721 token smart contract!
Expected output
Step 6: Creating the Contract Object
Now let’s look at the next function, getContract(). This function is pretty simple, it essentially create the contract object that will be used to interact with the ERC721 token smart contract. Copy the code below and paste it in the getContract() function.
const contractAddress = "INSERT_YOUR_CONTRACT_ADDRESS_HERE";  return new ethers.Contract(contractAddress, abi, signer);

For the first line of code, you will need to replace INSERT_YOUR_CONTRACT_ADDRESS_HERE with the address of your deployed ERC721 smart contract obtained from Quest 8. If you have lost your contract address, then you’ll need to repeat the contract deployment step of Quest 8 to get another contract address. This line of code ensures that the contract object is pointing to the correct smart contract.  

The second line of code, creates the contract object using the contract address, the smart contract Application Binary Interface (ABI) and the signer object that we have created in the previous step.  

The ABI of a smart contract provides specifications that allow smooth communication with external applications and other smart contracts. It does this by specifying details such as expected inputs, outputs, etc. You can think of the ABI as a mapping of the smart contract functions, their requirements and outputs. This is helpful in development as it provides developers with the list of available functions and their specifications when interacting with the smart contract.  

With this, we are now able to interact with our deployed smart contract on the Avalanche Fuji Testnet C-Chain using the contract object. In terms of frontend behavior changes, this would not trigger any change as we are merely creating the contract object. Only when you call one of the functions listed on the ABI will it trigger a transaction to the smart contract. 

Now that we have created our contract object, in the next step, we’ll be going through how to use it to call and interact with functions of our deployed smart contract.
Step 7: Using the Contract Object to Mint an NFT
How to start
Now that we have the contract object that is pointing to our deployed smart contract, we are now able to call the mint() function of our ERC721 token smart contract to mint some NFTs to our wallet! For a refresher on how this mint() function looks like, refer to the image in ‘How to start’.
Add the code below into the mintNFT() function.

const tx = await contract.mint(stringURI);  console.log("transaction:>> ", tx);  await tx.wait();  return tx;

In Quest 8, we learnt that the mint() function on the token smart contract takes in a tokenURI in the form of a string. So, the question is what is a token URI? Basically, a token URI is the metadata of an image such as the name, description and link to the image which in our case, would be the Pinata IPFS URL. Also, something to note here is that the ERC721 token smart contract does not return an output. 

For the first line of code, we will be calling the mint() function of the token smart contract and following its requirements, passing the token URI that has been converted to a string. While we have pointed out that the ERC721 token smart contract’s mint() function does not return an output, you may be wondering why are we assigning the output to the variable tx. The reason is that while the smart contract does not have an output, the contract object itself will return the transaction details of calling the mint() function.  

The third line of code is the wait() function where as the name states, it will wait till the block that the transaction is in has been published on the Fuji Testnet C-Chain before continuing. In a blockchain, blocks are not instantaneously published and the time it takes depends on the block size and the interval set by the blockchain's configuration. On average in Avalanche, block time is about 2-3 seconds depending on network conditions.

As you see from the function, the contract object and the stringURI is passed as input for the mintNFT() function so now let's take a look at the code in App.js to see how we are using the mintNFT() function.



Let’s open the App.js file and take a look at line 93 where the mintNFT() function is called. These lines of code will be triggered when matching pairs are found. You can see that the mintNFT() function takes in two variables here - the first is the tokenURI variable that has been generated based on image metadata and the second is the contract state variable which is the contract object that was created earlier.  

Once the NFT has been minted, it will update the updatedNFTList array of the minted NFTs data stored in the state variable mintedNFT. Then the data in the array will be displayed on the page itself.
Step 8: Playing the Game
Now that we know how the mintNFT() function works, all that’s left is the fun part - playing the game!
To recap, the goal of the game is to find pairs of cards with the same picture beneath them. Once you manage to find two cards with the same image, it will trigger the mintNFT() function to mint an NFT to your Core wallet.



So now let’s try matching two cards and see what the page shows. Once an image is matched, it will trigger Core to confirm that you want to proceed with the transaction, which is the minting process. Note that it is good practice to wait until the gas fees have been calculated before proceeding to approve the transaction (refer to image above).

Once the transaction is approved and the NFT is minted, you will see the NFT data on the webpage, as seen in the image in ‘Expected output’ below. The data includes a link to the token ID, a link to the SnowTrace block explorer with the transaction ID and a link to the image of your NFT hosted on IPFS. Note that the image of your NFT on IPFS might take up to a few seconds to render.
